[
    {
        "content": "<p>Given <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f : A \\to B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span>, is there some word that can refer to either <code>A</code> or <code>B</code> or both? An \"endpoint\" of <code>f</code> maybe?</p>",
        "id": 213453490,
        "sender_full_name": "Shea Levy",
        "timestamp": 1602780254
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(co)domain <span aria-label=\"stuck out tongue\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f61b\" role=\"img\" title=\"stuck out tongue\">:stuck_out_tongue:</span></p>",
        "id": 213454908,
        "sender_full_name": "Chad Nester",
        "timestamp": 1602780835
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Boundary?</p>",
        "id": 213455051,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1602780918
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(This terminology is grounded in the simplicial pov on categories)</p>",
        "id": 213456895,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1602781686
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(Not that it makes it better, though)</p>",
        "id": 213456938,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1602781707
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(In fact I like Chad's better <span aria-label=\"laughing\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f606\" role=\"img\" title=\"laughing\">:laughing:</span> )</p>",
        "id": 213456957,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1602781718
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>When would you use this term?</p>",
        "id": 213456969,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1602781724
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I actually use \"boundary\" when I'm drawing string diagrams, since in this case it's literally one of the boundaries of the diagram.</p>",
        "id": 213457745,
        "sender_full_name": "Chad Nester",
        "timestamp": 1602782100
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh right, in that context is perfect</p>",
        "id": 213457867,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1602782154
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>To my knowledge in standard category theory <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> are called <em>source</em> and <em>target</em>, respectively. Domain and codomain are also acceptable, even if those are mainly preferred when working with sets and functions.</p>",
        "id": 213464016,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1602784641
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I sometimes use 'source/target' to refer to A and B together (better, imho, than (co)domain)</p>",
        "id": 213495608,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1602800743
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276438\">Fabrizio Genovese</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Terminology.20capturing.20.22domain.22.20and.20.22codomain.22/near/213464016\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>To my knowledge in standard category theory <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> are called <em>source</em> and <em>target</em>, respectively. Domain and codomain are also acceptable, even if those are mainly preferred when working with sets and functions.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>personally i say domain/codomain much more often than source/target no matter what kind of category i'm working with <span aria-label=\"thinking\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f914\" role=\"img\" title=\"thinking\">:thinking:</span></p>",
        "id": 213506505,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1602809737
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Me too. But according to MacLane \"source/target\" is the preferred terminology, if I recall correctly</p>",
        "id": 213644434,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1602928920
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If I recall correctly, Mac Lane uses the ‘source/target’ terminology when talking about graphs</p>",
        "id": 213645094,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1602930048
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But then switches mostly to domain and codomain when talking about categories proper</p>",
        "id": 213645098,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1602930060
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the source/target terminology usually signifies that the categories being dealt with are ‘geometric’ or ‘small’ in some way</p>",
        "id": 213645123,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1602930122
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For example with internal categories</p>",
        "id": 213645167,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1602930153
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Clearly it should be \"the blunt end\" and \"the pointy end\"</p>",
        "id": 213646093,
        "sender_full_name": "Jules Hedges",
        "timestamp": 1602931694
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"341237\">Fawzi Hreiki</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Terminology.20capturing.20.22domain.22.20and.20.22codomain.22/near/213645123\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think the source/target terminology usually signifies that the categories being dealt with are ‘geometric’ or ‘small’ in some way</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This feels like the sort of thing done by people who define a groupoid to be a <strong>small</strong> category with all arrows invertible.</p>",
        "id": 213693536,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1603006173
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>domain/codomain captures the duality nicely. A morphism in the dual of a category goes from its codomain to its cocodomain <span aria-label=\"wink\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f609\" role=\"img\" title=\"wink\">:wink:</span></p>",
        "id": 213698791,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1603014682
    }
]